The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
Per the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our carriers offer virtually all the services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing here – a virtual trader that forces the traditional to lower the price.
It may not be missing for a long time.
The fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, ČTÚ also confirmed this, noting that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the Union.
Following the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise – for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that would really want to start the clash.
It may sound absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
Instead, mobile telephone operators like to lament the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has often stressed that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is true that the traditional operator with its own network is no longer likely to have many possibilities. (Out of the way maybe it would be difficult now to find other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility -the virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry into the market of virtual traders that has led to a significant price drop, to which traditional traders would then have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, rumors resounded in Britain similar to ours.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can really succeed.
For example, we should not go too far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta to which in the Czech Republic belongs, among others, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual traders is the ability to focus on a much more concrete group-to-group.
In order to function effectively, it requires much fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry back, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at a low cost, they offer low-cost calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the narrower offer of services.
So for example Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a fairly good move to bet on a group-breaker not so long ago.
This operator focuses, so to speak, specifically on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and who they can trust," says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if we can claim a similar concept as in Poland.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, from the service point of view it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have much expectation.
The activation of Mobilking will take place rather in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone conversation with Mobile.cz.
He therefore indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very favourable to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything so that you do not create any potential competitor.
For a while, he has not hidden his interest in launching a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor to Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And sooner it is better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them,” said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe better times will come.
From the unofficial information it appears that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, a wall of silence is erected around his creation.
“At the moment we do not believe that there is room for the creation of a full-time virtual trader in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefónica O2 said in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also resort to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "So far we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue building."
And he adds: “There will hardly be a virtual operator on the T-Mobil network by the end of the year.
At this point we would have had to have a concrete agreement on the table so that it could be considered at the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses on meeting its 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual traders, especially in terms of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the customer’s point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities – with complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to decreased profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The disturbances surrounding the creation of U:fon testify that when the operators hold onto a thing, they can remove on the same side.
Per the great pressure was on ČTÚ during the creation period of U:fon to the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly accessible information from ČTÚ’s websites.
But now just U:fon serves as an argument for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: “The competitive environment in the mobile market has been slightly enhanced with the entrance of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would put high demands on him and especially on his services.”
The attitude of mobile operators is surprising, however, the complete disinterest by the Czech regulators.
It is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ that, unfortunately, in the Czech Republic – unlike Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position on the whole issue.
“The virtual operator’s entry into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the lease agreement for the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers probably has not been interesting enough for traditional traders,” said Kristián Chalupa, of the ÚOHS External Relations Department, in response to our question.
This statement by the representatives of the operators may not be surprising.
Instead, by the office, which must defend the interests of consumers and, moreover, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate affair.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: “In the overseas where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services.”
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices are not in the interests of ÚOHS.
Really shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises by itself.
Just as the same price of gasoline for all gas stations is the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
“The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No trader has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its behavior on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile network market to virtual operators may also be lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is the relevant market analysis by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech trader has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the operator of the network.
And the mobile operator has – logically in the end – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion must be dominant by force.
But even if we didn’t admit this argument, for ÚOHS it should be a minimum alarming that three mobile operators proceed so strangely similarly.
At the same time, complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all traders they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading the responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS keeps itself out of all the matter.
We have seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ’s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently passed telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that, from this, many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of ÚOHS must know more than well, but their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one looks.
While we are unaware of the functioning of such pseudo-virtual operators, some of which even exist in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their mobile phone price lists, which are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company versus the operator appears as a classic corporate customer, who orders a lot of SIM cards.
As a major customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
“If the cases you discuss, which we will be interested in, arise, it could be a breach of contractual conditions, and could lead to the termination of cooperation with this company,” said Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the 3 mentioned companies it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends itself at the same time against such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they draw a profit not indifferent and at the same time - unlike real virtual traders - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: “The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they can’t dispose of it in full as regular customers of mobile operators.”
But this should be a little strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another issue opens up for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to unmask such activities and if it did not want it, it will not have to be contented with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their business conditions prohibit it.
When it is no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The themes they used were virtually identical – too small market, too saturated boundary, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries, regulators have intervened in these cases to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then we came to the creation of the first virtual operator and others came to him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies throw everything from one to the other like a boiling potato.
By our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let’s not throw the sponge.
If the backstory information is correct and the virtual operator will really appear to us soon, the Czech mobile market will get back in motion.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only hardly ÚOHS could remain impassible to the rejection (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the Day of recognition of the Czech state presented in a solemn manner the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the anthem was made by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, choral step and instrumental edition.
The song is directed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the revisions of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the website iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
He previously told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he has chosen specifically to sing the variants alone, singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried to make sure that both and the choir, have a clear dictionary, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh theatre in the original opera Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
It acquired popularity and people spontaneously made it theirs.
The first strofe of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
