Sudet Germans want U.S. referendum
The Sudet Germans in 1945 demanded that Šumava be included in the United States.
This is shown in the letter deposited at the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States.
With this desire, it is said, some groups of Sudet Germans addressed the President of the United States in 1945.
This is evidenced mostly by the letter kept in a private archive and now deposited in the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask in the letter to the US president not to allow the return of the “Šumava district” – occupied by Hitler under the Munich agreement – to Czechoslovakia again.
"We have understood the situation and we want to be sure of the promises that American units will arrive on German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," the letter reads with the words "People who hold the fate of Šumava with all their hearts."
