Even rats have feelings.
A rat or a cockroach escape when they feel the danger.
The neuroscientist Joseph Le Doux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how could it happen if, when they behave in our same way, they have our same feelings?
On the Internet newspaper "Edge" for several years articles of well-known scientists are published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in a series presents selected answers to the question: "What do you think is true, without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings or other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove it so far, since we cannot even prove that other men have consciousness.
But in this case we must at least hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and ask questions about feelings or consciousness in general, we enter an impractical territory, because the reference base does not match.
When a rat is in a dangerous situation, it does the same things that other animals do.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists understand that there is a comparable subjective feeling.
I do not believe this.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult for us to convey our feelings to animals.
On the one hand, the lateral prefrontal cortex is often connected to human consciousness, associated circuits (this is due to its direct participation in short memory and executive and control functions).
In man this wide area is much more developed than in other primates, and it seems that among other creatures it is completely missing.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including knowledge, who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, we thus admit the foundation on the assumption that man differs even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity should appear in the man’s way of speaking: since much of life is connected to language, it is often said that it is connected to consciousness.
In this case, animals may be excluded.
Although consciousness does not depend on language, it would influence it in such a way that the consciousness of the animal, as it is made, differs greatly from the circumstances of our consciousness.
This is why it is difficult to find out how consciousness can be seen in other animals.
If it is not possible to measure it as an internal and subjective thing, in analyzing it through our own experience due to the special hardware, their research will put us in big trouble.
Most interpretations refer to the content of conscious experience, but apart from this there is another aspect of consciousness to which science would have easier access.
You could analyze the processes of animal consciousness regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in the studies on the short memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
So for this principle, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick follow, we go to the neural correlates of consciousness rather than the causal mechanisms: both may be identical but not necessarily.
Interestingly, this principle also highlights the value of the prefrontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
What is therefore outlined for feelings?
I blame them for the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in one of their conscious brain activities.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as body reactions) occupies the working memory.
Thus, the feelings are closely connected to the regions of the cortex, which characterize the primates and in particular the human being.
With the speaking nature, subtle nuances of feeling are created, because with the help of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize situations, to describe them to others.
Compared to this, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that the feelings result from more primitive activities of the body regions of the sensations of the cortex and paleo-head, similar to Jack Pankseep, who, however, focused more on the paleo-cephalus.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, this could definitely be part of the feelings extended to the species.
On a purely theoretical level, I cannot contradict this, but I find it undemonstrable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to rats and humans as fear is probably so perceived by the senses in both cases: but how could it happen if rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach in case of danger flees as if he felt the fear too?
In my eyes, the mere resemblance of behavior cannot yet prove any vital resemblance.
And that is, the neural comparison continues to be helpful: rats and humans have similar paleoencephals, and cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the paleoencephalus responsible for emotions?
And if you could prove it for humans, how would you want to prove it for rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even insects (who knows?), have feelings.
I did not know how to prove it.
And since their feelings are fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on specific circuits and language), I prefer to study emotional behavior rather than rats’ emotional sensations.
In any case, there is some progress here at the neural level, as long as you give up the same procedure on rats and men.
Just as I don’t do research on language and consciousness in rats, so I don’t do it on their emotions, I don’t even know if they exist.
This may be considered short-sighted, but I prefer to take steps forward, rather than constantly hitting a wall.
I am a practical emotional.
