In a separate city, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the extensive theme park in the suburbs of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the enormous, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city incorporated into the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools, and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, the most famous Harlem Renaissance writer.
And yet in many ways, the city that he described — and that makes tourists stop by understanding it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project — remains a place apart.
She’s as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that “knowing so little about us, she doesn’t know what she’s losing.”
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening speech on race, many here remain suspicious of the outsider’s gaze.
“We’re very careful about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
“It must be fair.”
Eatonville has long been described as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historic model of black power-taking and a community of almost 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oak of the southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And concern for the image of Eatonville really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Rout 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten downtown of Florida within a scenario of black history and human drama.
Low as a dwarf in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then deviated to more private areas.
"Out of the street on the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-maintained gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked at, thinking he could barely read and write."
She also mentioned Widow Dash’s new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the passing rooms.”
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriages and sex.
Clearly this was not Fodor’s.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora said it as it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90 years old, one of Johnson's girls that Hurston immortalizes by quoting men singing rough songs about their beauty.
He added: “Some people don’t like it.”
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston plunged into the city, he usually arrived without notice in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts decent clothing today.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others subdued.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” said Mr. Franklin.
But, she added, swinging on her chair on the courtyard on the back of Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, “she never stayed long.”
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Together with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a star of literature, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a plaque-free tomb in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville, there were no major commemorative ceremonies, and no major conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-track highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-track road.
The expansion of Orlando has already pushed the Interstate 4 across the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period of its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community’s doorstep.
“During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things to the people sitting on one side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girlfriend who was killed by that once.
They threw a cockroach out of a car.”
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race."
Residents now say that the segregation of schools, despite being positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and puts the confidence of its young people at risk.
“Black kids were used to being hugged – I remember this – you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins’ daughter and executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
“You didn’t embrace your white teacher because your white teacher...– I mean, there’s a cultural division there,” Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, anyway, helped and created space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons – black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like, “How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I can’t really understand.”
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston's plain tomb and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, Robert E. Hemenway’s acclaimed biography on Hurston hit the bookstores shelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as her most famous daughter had tossed the highway lights again.
And this time, Hurston’s old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many come back for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state withdrew from its road project.
“The five lanes of the resurrected highway brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city,” said Ms. Nathiri.
Ms. Boyd puts it simpler: “Zora saved Eatonville.”
The victory on the highway project helped change the image that the city has of itself.
Those from outside town like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the Public Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a refurbished and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a secondary road under the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1800s.
(It is 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for the history of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A requested permission is required for most of the interviews, and some things – such as wall paintings on Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields – are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a fat teacher, with a weak for bright red, still fears that their island community will be misunderstood.
However, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of citizen pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, troubled and everything, neither better nor worse and proud, creative, great-working, stupid and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection what can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, who he said might need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“Many people, if they’ve just entered here, will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” said Alondra Kenon after Mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a cute city.”
