"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no rides, no clothes from before.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in the private, in those moments away from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of the hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatricality of some shots of singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the less known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, growing every day," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" they may also be ordinary people, but by seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the stage.
These people portrayed "on the road" are "artists able to convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and capture the audience.
In order to capture the personality of these great ones, it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
Because their personality and character are internal.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture the personality of the big flamenco with the camera.”
With a passion for the "Cante de las Minas" festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to portray singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
These are portraits that, due to the type of machine and material, resemble classical photography.
The application of various stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of image, giving photography modernity, according to an idea that reflects Bauer's own concept of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not the dance, the singing or the playing in itself, but the artist’s personality, his character, able to conquer the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, appear in this selection of about seventy portrayed artists.
The project has become a sort of flamenco anthology, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits displayed at the time of the exhibition.
The passion for portraits led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love portraying people, knowing them and being able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or short moment.
I think portrait is the most difficult genre in photography.
You meet or compare with people, characters you sometimes don’t even know or who give you just a few minutes to take the photo.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to concrete my ideas.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people" is set up at the gallery El Fotómata, at number 20 of via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until the next 16 October.
