Drivers with recurrent alcoholism will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of Internal Affairs requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive level of alcohol in the blood, install in their car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in the state of drunkenness or if it does not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the General Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since he will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the General Prosecutor’s Office for Road Safety, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Foundation Institute of Technology for Automotive Safety (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers who have been more than once for drunk driving then return to driving.
Alcolock would avoid this, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from getting started if the driver does not blow, or when a higher alcohol concentration than permitted is detected.
The cost is more than 1,000 euros and would be borne by the penalty.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices reduce offenses committed during the first year of introduction by up to 65%.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb such behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, undoubtedly, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
The device, however, is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a PSOE initiative that proposes to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
