Speaking in Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I’m not referring to those who wake up very upset to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while they are asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get a scare, but it doesn’t really matter.
This is a benign sleep disturbance called somnilochia.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with an episode of high fever) or with a greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis, or sleeping, but it is not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with stages of very high fever, stressful situations or over-excitation.
However, this is still a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper, or that the opposite happens (crying, screaming, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and eventually consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a outflow to the situation.
We said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stressful situation).
What can be done, however, is to consider a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to exaggerate the baby before he goes to bed.
Offer quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tired to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the somniloquis appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the baby and that the next day he will not remember anything about what happened.
Useful advice
Do not wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he’s talking, he’s sleeping and so he’s resting.
Remember that if it appears very anxious and the episodes have a certain frequency it is best to consult a doctor or check where such a great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), don’t fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not to see what he is dreaming to say, so you need to pay much attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions it may lead to.
Never tell your child that you might ask him questions during the night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
This kind of thing causes great anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing serious, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
