Blood is Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Decary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the infected blood scandal in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, directed by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent a reoccurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee to design a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, this mandate was executed by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all the other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its business, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the Québec donation system, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was mortificating.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood sampling and field research over the following years, we have regained public confidence,” she explains before stating proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Québec’s population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that “confidence is something extremely fragile.”
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its foundation.
"And we didn't know absolutely whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could get a serious illness, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that manifests with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, take exclusion measures.
In April 1999, blood was rejected from those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without a doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it makes sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (TAN) that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment the person contracted the disease to the one in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to identify them has thus been greatly reduced.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will need to be distributed before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a transmitted HIV case is detected.
I believe that today one can feel safe in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant,” continues Dr. Décary before emphasizing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
“The needs are increasing as the population ages.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors that on average make up only 3% of Quebec’s accepted donors.”
All healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortage are very rare.
But members of this group of donors need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but most importantly to hold them back and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so busy that you can hardly have an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eye balloons, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec that runs the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Québec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abundant blood rich in stem cells that can be used to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the placement in the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice as very popular.
“Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it,” as Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals in Québec.
