Title: A Disgraceful Country
It was Vic Toews, the former Harper Cabinet Justice Minister, who allowed himself to declare, last summer, that Louise Arbor was a “shame” for Canada.
To dishonor in this way a woman who has fought unceasingly for justice and who deserves all our admiration says a lot about both the prime minister’s surroundings and Stephen Harper himself.
Here we are facing a government that is the only of all the Western countries involved that has not repatriated a citizen detained in the Guantanamo concentration camp.
A government that doesn’t take into account the fact that Omar Khadr was just a teenager at the time of the accusations.
The only government that, despite signing the Geneva Convention, denies its promise and drops a child-soldat in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a parody of justice to establish the guilt of the accused.
We remind, for information, that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, in particular, are calling for Omar Khadraffin’s return so that he can be subjected to a regular trial in Canada.
It is the same government that closes its eyes to torture: it does not care that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, forever, after so many years of oppression.
We don’t realize it yet, but we’re witnessing an insidious erosion of our rights, freedom and “democracy,” a word that Harper doesn’t stop pronouncing and sounds so nonsensical on his lips.
Here we have come to the moment when there is no more morality: one can abuse, torture, arbitrarily imprison a Canadian citizen at the discretion of a leader of government so far a minority (see what will happen after October 14 ...).
Many voters believe that a party that preaches virtue, respect for law and order represents salvation: they do not see that this government has given up what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
Here is the shame, Mr Toews, in giving up all this, and nowhere else.
The Orwell Discourse of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house shattered with the intention of initiating a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Canada Black will have to spend a substantial sum of money in order to organize their defence and fight, with decisively unarmed weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the virtually unfunded pockets of the mining company.
By the way, in these unarmed arms struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that outrages the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to rule again on the matter.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it would have been in front of the public that he should have presented his view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates usually take place through the exchange of opinions and not on a scroll.
It would then have been enough for the society to open its books, its documents, and set up a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to have too much confidence in the public and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of Black Canada authors.
Per Garver could explain how he can call for a "public debate" when his contempt for that same audience is obvious?
In the vice president’s world, it seems that this word only refers to the scentfully paid lawyers and not the whole of Canadians; here’s a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrants have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold does not understand – or does not want to understand – is that the public that supports the writers and publishers of Canada Black does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This public is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilian exchanges of opinions, and not in the light of what many perceive as a kind of bullying (seeking the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Black an ultimatum urging them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, Barrack Gold’s complaint is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies the right to citation of authentic sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which constitute the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss issues that are uncomfortable to the richest companies in the world, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific standards like the Black Canada authors do.
He has the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The excessive measures of Barrick Gold clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is at the expense of the academic world, as is the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit abusive lawsuits.
