In particular, it provides for checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to guarantee the refund of public money, new provisions to contain the number of homes seized for non-payment, as well as a right to inspect salaries paid to managers of protected companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
“We’ve made great progress towards an effective market deal,” Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
“Every decision was made in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the current Wall Street crisis,” he said.
“This is the crucial point: if we hadn’t acted in this way, invaluable distress and disturbance would have been poured out on the daily lives of Americans,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of another bankruptcy on investors.
The deadline agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
United later to the negotiation, the two U.S. presidential candidates were quite in favour of the agreement, but did not avoid expressing their dissatisfaction with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has added a number of provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow owners to keep their homes and the one inherent in salaries for executives of state-backed companies.
“When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he said on the US television screen.
Interviewed on another channel to know if he would vote for the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope it does."
"According to what I've read, it's something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward."
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsold assets of U.S. financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the burst of a real estate bubble that has led first to the collapse of mortgages, then extended to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and resulted in the freezing of liquidity and banking and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in office that sent the first draft of an agreement to the air last week.
They seem to have come out of that blind street since Democrats accepted that the “toxic” assets of some troubled companies are only being protected by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to meet everyone, a provision was added to Congress that if the government had to face losses over the next five years due to such a program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan includes a first payment of $250 billion to which another $100 billion may be added if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion should be ratified by a further congressional vote.
In exchange for its aid, Washington will get shares in the protected companies that will pay dividends in the event of profit and that it will be able to revend when the waters have calmed down.
As set out in the plan, the federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures related to real estate loans and to set limits on remuneration and start-up allowances paid to executives of the companies involved.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to submit it to the House of Representatives vote, and the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be given a free way.
In fact, yesterday there were several votes against the bill, both in the Republican and Democratic sides.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House’s finance committee.
“We have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
Not to take advantage of taxpayers.
Leader of a small group in Congress nicknamed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to say: we ask Congress not to draw hasty conclusions and carefully examine the way to go,” he said.
At the same time, Europe was once again witnessing the global nature of the crisis.
Following an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for €11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary when the French bank BNS Paribas announced that it would give up the purchase of its competitor, in full bankruptcy after the loss of €2 billion ($2.9 billion) due to the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis has 85,000 employees and is one of the 20 largest banks in Europe and the 10 largest insurance companies.
“It’s not the lost money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said.
In exchange, influence and voting rights are gained in banking matters.
It is something that savers and families appreciate now that the times are uncertain.”
During this period, at the other end of the Channel, the British government appears to be on the verge of nationalizing another bank in danger of the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all of the loans currently ongoing at the bank Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion ($75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander has announced that it will be in charge of buying the bank’s branches and customer accounts.
Since the beginning of the economic crisis, Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to undergo a process of nationalization by the British government.
