What was produced in the Zuschlag & Soci facturing factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearing of the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and associates will be discussed.
The politician and his associates are charged with repeated commercial fraud committed within a criminal association that has caused considerable damage, and other crimes, including falsification of documents.
According to the Prosecutor’s Office, the money obtained from competitions was used by them for private purposes, and they often certified the performance of the activities through fake invoices.
The state and municipal money, a total of 65 million florins, ended in part in the box office of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, in part in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, disclosed by the investigating authorities, they withdrew the money obtained from tenders on the basis of bills for non-existent transactions and the associations never complied with their obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were fake.
In order to do so, the bill blocks were purchased at the Józsefváros market, while the circular stamps were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which companies to issue the invoices, it was established, among other things, during the trip through the hills above the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter’s confession, he had to choose between pensions and restaurants.
He requested an invoice for consumptions, on the model of which the invoices were prepared to be submitted to the competition calls, among others, to those of the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András Őri who, according to our information, mainly drafted the reports necessary to obtain funding.
One of the choices of Lados' "study trip" was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and partners in 2003, the restaurant provided meals to a group of 90 people of the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
So many people, however, according to the restaurant owner, would not all enter the room together.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later referred to as Együtt in Harmadik Évezredért, was full of formal and content errors.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay there, however the bill included 130 guests.
But the fanciful bill compilers exaggerated when they Pigal Kft., which also deals with catering, whose accounting — according to the information released to the judicial authorities — did not even include the documents on behalf of the companies Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the company’s manager, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor’s office and the bills were shown to him, he immediately understood that the documents were fake.
“On the stamp, our company’s name and VAT item were in the wrong place.”
He added: in addition to the formal reasons did not even the fact that according to the invoice were housed a hundred people, when in total they have eleven rooms and there are not so many beds.
The restaurant has been out of service for a long time, and the restaurant is no longer in operation.
The hard-working bill compilers did not worry to find out that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only organizes trips abroad, so they foolishly indicated on the invoice with cash travel to Hungary, which was not in accordance with the company’s practice of issuing invoices.
In addition, as demonstrated during the investigation, VAT was also included in the invoice, while travel activities to countries outside the European Union are exempt from VAT.
Among other things, the amount of VAT was also wrong on the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favour of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, in fact on the services offered by the company must be applied VAT at 15% and not at 25% as indicated on the invoices, in addition the hotel employees issued only printed invoices, while the manufactured invoice was written by hand.
In addition to this, the "emitents" ruined other invoices, in the case of a company they indicated as the activity carried out the transportation of goods on the road, as is apparent from the proceedings of the Prosecutor's Office, activity that was not carried out by the company originally founded for investment advice.
In addition, for formal defects - due to non-compliant invoice format, false stamp - it was found that the invoices issued in favour of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI.
The same was the case for Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Field, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The counterfeiters did not pay attention even to the fact that the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when (2001) a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület dined there, which is why the liquidation curator of the company, according to our information, denied that he had issued that invoice.
They consciously issued invoices.
Another group of invoice issuers consisted of those who knew they had to issue fictitious invoices.
Esély Budapestért Alapítvány issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal – Ifjú Szocialisták in favour of the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért of 4 million florins.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the accused, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
He also collaborated with Zuschlag and associates with the currently in liquidation Biogate Kft, which in 2003 issued invoices worth approximately 5 million florins to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány, the Atlasz Egyesület and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület, behind which there was no real economic activity.
No movement of money because the prepared bills were then overturned, but the associations forgot to include this aspect in their documents.
The following group of firms issuing invoices include those that are connected with the accused.
For example, Ivan Kubatov, authorized at the address of the CEO of Delta Trió Kft, headquartered in Budapest but not found there, who deals with fuel and motor vehicle trade.
The company issued various invoices in October, November and December 2005 related to the sale of computer equipment, worth about 18 million florins.
According to the data of the investigation, Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas under liquidation since 14 September 2005 purchased these invoices.
The CEO of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov would have handed over the documents concerning the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, during the investigation, Kubatov admitted that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt at Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that the amount was collected from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov, Romanian millers founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
However, none of the companies were operative, because according to the accused they had not received work.
However, the companies returned to him because at the request of the co-accused lawyer Zsolt Szente, editor of the company’s founding documents, in the name of the companies, invoices were issued to the associations linked to Zuschlag: Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
On behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade Kubatov issued 15 invoices for a total value of 14.2 million florins.
The prosecution believes that Kubatov has stolen 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices, as well as VAT.
The man also used the Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, manufactured for the Biztos Pont competition.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 submitted a tender for the Socialist Party’s public utility organization, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 florins per capita but the money was not used for the purposes indicated in the call.
To prevent this from happening, they submitted to TMA five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These bills were found during the search of Árpád Kemecsei’s office at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, a part of the accused, as they have already done at the prosecutor's office, will probably report on the development of the invoices.
However, the most interesting thing could be if the accused number one, János Zuschlag, decided to lift the veil on everything.
His confession so far has not been very detailed and although he has promised several times to talk about everything in an extensive way, he has not yet done it.
It is necessary to see if it is in his interest, it may also happen that the socialists have made agreements with Zusi, who - in exchange for a compensation of 50 million florins, much of the damage - would be willing to do the expiatory goat.
Zuschlag could have offended himself as his demands to ease his conditions in prison, i.e. to grant house arrest, have not yet been met.
While the perpetrators of non-reparable commercial crimes and causing much greater damage can freely walk or at least wait at home for the end of the proceedings against them, which is not granted to him.
The psychology of overbidding: why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, to overvalu the goods.
Neurologists and research economists at the University of New York have managed to uncover the neuro-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to stay behind in a competition such as an eBay auction, so they are willing to pay even a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nerve pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in a auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bet more than the other, the stripped body under the cerebral cortex enters into intensive function when you lose the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in price is explained by scanning the fierce reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the research group’s economists conducted a financial investigation.
In this survey, three groups bid against a partner under different conditions.
They to the control group the actual value of the product in question and they made their bet.
In addition to this, they promised another group that in case of winning they would receive another $15 prize.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose the money if they lost the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
Testing the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the group that played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "win".
"These findings are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, these so far explained the phenomena seen at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped solve the contradiction between the two theories, so we have come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to go to the doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients amounts to hundreds of thousands, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many sick people do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and iritis, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to get vaccinated against the virus A and B, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and white of the eyes, the stool becomes clear and the urine dark, healing occurs within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtilly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, prevention and regular medical examinations are very important.
This disease is much more common than average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooers.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worth referring to your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
The World Hepatitis Day is celebrated on September 30th, and was first held worldwide in 2004 by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the results of a recent survey, religious faith works as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more tolerable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph.
As part of the bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were electro-shocked, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to repel much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploration technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first of a series of researches in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also participate.
The test went exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electro shock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the hermit of Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would originate a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
The subjects in the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and during this time they received 20 electro-shocks in four consecutive series, while watching either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel “safe,” as if “somebody was taking care” of them, and “they reassured themselves and were pervaded by peace.”
Looking at the religious-themed image, they accounted for 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the test, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but it is necessary to find the appropriate image.
"We must look for an image towards which they feed very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it manages to change our personality." - Wright added.
After the excellent results remains only the question of whether the painting of a Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to the believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
