On the day of their tenth birthday, Google can claim to be in people’s pockets as much as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which outpatient they attend and what they care about.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the CEOs of the company, this is not enough yet.
As for the skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they don’t really see the substance of the web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s primary purpose is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google’s founders that was: “we put all the information in the world in one system!”
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to handle all the information.
Asked what would happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to answer questions like “What am I doing tomorrow?” or “What would be the right job for me?” but software doesn’t answer seemingly simple questions because they don’t know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their internet searches the exact searches are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search started two years ago, users can store their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these will then in the long run generate much better tailored results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What if my data is used against me, if they look at what I’m dealing with? – they ask users concerned about Google’s data monopoly.
In most cases, the counter-reactions of internet users are provoked by the fear of the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the sense of guilt, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom, or even the rebellion to power.
One fact is confirmed, however, and that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community pageined by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights, on the other hand, soup of relief in May when the company - in agreement with the e-law protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even after that it can not be forced Google with any point of the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully ripped almost 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search phrases obtained in reference to the confirmation of the Child Protection Act passed years earlier, but still failed to get individual user search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
The judgment of Google is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data spy on Google because they believe that it will affect their intimate sphere and privacy by starting to use its services and rise with the rebellion due to the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users in numerous countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as the world conqueror because of Windows, although they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is always kept up to date and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies just one of the most frequently repeated keywords in recent years, the web 2.0.
The web 2.0 speaks of collaboration, of intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: showing ourselves.
A young average can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, all of these can place them in systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which automatically appear his latest photo galleries stored on Flickr or on Picasa.
