The smart car imitates the flight of the crab
What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies other than mimicking the obstacle sensors found in nature?
For example the bees.
In the stunning project presented at CEATEC in Japan, cranes gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic clue on how to build the next generation of collision-proof systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-car with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really resembles our protective shield - explained at the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR technologies and research and development sector.
Important is the role of the bee's vision, capable of a 300-degree view in each direction.
The engineers used the telemetry laser idea to copy the function of bee vision.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This maneuver of avoidance, in a way different from the current system, takes place in a very instinctive way.
“If it were not so, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Lab and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging, inner layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in a blink of eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of wheel steering.
Thus, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan other bees, the robot, as available possibilities, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a high energy density, which means that they last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of the smart reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot must process some input in seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few dozen Kb.
There is no need for a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards developing an immediate collision-preventing technology that Nissan predicts will be installed on standard vehicles within 10 years.
Additional application possibility can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that by avoiding obstacles present on the road leads to the destination.
