MP3 Players Accused, Puting Hearing at Risk
Listening to high-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission reports, citing the opinion of the EU Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (Csrseri) published today.
“This scientific opinion shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day while holding the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity.”
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at high noise levels can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
“The scientific findings show a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is that we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with new technology.”
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the widespread use of portable musical instruments and the increasing number of young people exposed to their noise.
Scientists confirm that there is reason for concern and the European Commission will now, together with Member States and stakeholders, consider what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and related equipment.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
This damage can be greatly limited by using solutions such as reducing the levels and duration of noise exposure.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music equipment listening to music in high volume (over 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceeds the currently applicable maximum noise limits at work.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods are at risk of a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
