Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the House of Representatives vote against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
The New York Times of yesterday confirmed that the ongoing crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "washington" and the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, for instance, which became prepotently alive with the vow of which I said in the beginning.
This, however, is only one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the ongoing economic earthquake foretells or already shows: not only in the United States but throughout the West and not even here alone.
Both in the United States and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate long-incubated phenomena that solidify in the new climate and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary rise, of the double category State-Sovereignty in relation to a sort of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, close ties with the outside world, but which first and foremost see the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, involved in a very large extent.
What immediately creates a political problem for those who rule it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and those families who, by the way, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be globally economic, but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of play or has little to say: the striking proof is given by the European Union that divides as usual between different interests and between different state strategies fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, plans of rescue and relief, new rules, and above all funding: since when you get to the narrow are only the states who own the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in the sixth.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of incommensurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market or international organization will ever be able to dispose in a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the status-national element is in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the intangible, while we were convinced that the globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal with those very little intangible things that are water, harvests, oil.
All things that, look a little, can be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still connected in an absolute way to a confined space, to a territory.
So the one who finds himself to be a sovereign has many more cards than the one who is not, the one who is unlucky to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, which presupposes a fracture.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand for someone who knows how to take over the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species, revealed so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And at the same time something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: a discredit, an insufficiency, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
That is to say, it seems that in vast sectors of the population, the belief that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far in rise, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, has made their own time and is increasingly foreign to the opinions of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly nourishes a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolts" of the elections or in the sudden upsurges of the collective moods of recent and most recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of American congressmen against Bush (and even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
There is the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say somebody, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not from today taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is revitalizing, increasing, potentially agitating to excess.
